@Initial revision
@
text
@a209 19
The filesystem uses GNU's re-enterant malloc, et al. to get memory to hold its
data structures, buffers, etc. These functions allocate memory from a private
pool reserved explicitly to the filesystem. A single memory pool is used for
all volumes. FSYS_POOL_SIZE sets the size (in bytes) of this pool. The default
is 128k allowing for approximately 1000 files in the volume(s). A writeable
filesystem with 1000 files will require much more memory than 128k.

NOTE: on a READ_ONLY filesystem, once the volume has been mounted, no
further malloc's are performed. One may check the resuidual value of
of the static variable 'free_size' in fsys.c after all mounts have
completed and adjust the value assigned to FSYS_POOL_SIZE to retrieve
some unused memory if desired.
*/

#ifndef FSYS_POOL_SIZE
# define FSYS_POOL_SIZE (128*1024)	/* amount of memory filesystem can use */
#endif

